<HEADLINE>
FT  11 NOV 94 / London Stock Exchange: Two-way pull in Royals
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER JOHN, JOEL KIBAZO and JEFFREY BROWN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The stock market took a churlish view of third-quarter profits from Royal
Insurance and the shares dropped almost 20p after the headline figure was
announced.
Subsequent reappraisal of underlying nuances in the results prompted furious
two-way trading which saw turnover of 15m shares. The volume was the highest
since February 1992 but then Royal had announced that its losses had plunged
to Pounds 373m and shareholders would receive no dividend.
The picture yesterday was altogether brighter. Nine-month profits came in at
Pounds 311m, against Pounds 113m a year ago, and although they were at the
lower end of forecasts some analysts had been over enthusiastic following
bumper second-quarter figures. The main hit of Pounds 19m came from the
rebalancing of Royals' investment portfolio - the group has spent the last
year shifting Pounds 400m from bonds to equities. But Mr Charles Landa of
SGST, remained positive on the stock, arguing that Royals was 'sacrificing
investment income today for capital growth tomorrow'.
Analysts also said the presentation was impressively upbeat. The shares,
which have performed very strongly over the past few weeks, rallied from
their low but closed 5 off at 295p.
</TEXT>
