<HEADLINE>
FT  11 NOV 94 / World Stock Markets (America): Initial Dow rise reversed as
bonds turn
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA BRANSTEN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US shares climbed early yesterday on the heels of rising bond prices, before
falling into negative territory later on profit-taking and a downturn in the
bond market, writes Lisa Bransten in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average ended 9.76 down at 3,821.99. The Standard &amp;
Poor's 500 lost 1.03 at 464.37, while the American SE composite shed 1.66 to
449.59 and the Nasdaq composite 2.87 to 764.38. NYSE volume came to 282m
shares.
The producer price index declined by 0.5 per cent in October, exactly
matching September's movement  - most analysts were expecting a 0.1 per cent
increase.
However, few economists wavered from their forecasts that the Federal
Reserve would tighten monetary policy by raising interest rates by at least
50 basis points at next Tuesday's open market committee meeting. Analysts
said the positive PPI figure decreased the likelihood that the Fed would
make the 100 basis-point increase some had been anticipating.
Markets see-sawed for the second consecutive day yesterday following
unsteady bond prices. Wednesday's session was volatile amid uncertainties
regarding the economic impact of Republican victories in congressional
elections.
Late in the morning session the Dow had gained nearly 25 points as the
30-year Treasury bond rose, but declined as the long bond lost  3/8 late in
the day and the dollar fell to its late Wednesday price against the Japanese
yen.
Sears Roebuck jumped Dollars 2 3/4 to Dollars 51 3/8 after the retailer
announced its intention to spin off its 80 per cent stake in the insurance
subsidiary Allstate next year. Under this plan, Sears' shareholders would
receive approximately one share in Allstate for each Sears share presently
held. Allstate fell Dollars  3/4 to Dollars 24 1/8 on the news.
Shares in US computer-chip makers declined after an industry report, issued
late on Wednesday, indicated that sector growth for October was not as
strong as many analysts had predicted. Industry bellwether Intel, which is
traded on the Nasdaq, dipped Dollars  1/8 to Dollars 61 1/8 , Texas
Instruments Dollars 1 3/4 to Dollars 77 and National Semiconductor Dollars
3/8 to Dollars 17 5/8 .
Telefonos de Mexico declined sharply on news that it will face tough
competition from a Dollars 1bn joint venture, announced Wednesday, between
telecommunications giant AT&amp;T and Mexico's Grupo Industrial Alfa. By the
close, Telmex ADRs were down Dollars 4 3/4 at Dollars 51 1/4 . AT&amp;T and Alfa
plan to begin operations next year and apply for a licence to provide
long-distance service so that it will be ready to compete when that market
is opened for full competition in January 1997.
Greyhound Lines slipped Dollars  1/16 to Dollars 2 3/16 on news that the
beleaguered bus company had rejected a new reorganisation proposal from its
bondholders.
Caterpillar gained slightly in the morning after announcing on Wednesday
that it would increase prices of North American machines and engines, but
fell with the rest of the market to end Dollars  3/8 off at Dollars 58.
Canada
Initial gains were washed away once again, as the weakening in the bond
markets sent share prices lower late in the session. The TSE 300 index
finished 12.19 down at 4,179.19 in volume of 51.3m shares.
Mexico
The bolsa registered its fourth biggest fall of 1994 as investors piled out
of Telefonos de Mexico (Telmex) after a number of brokers downgraded the
issue following AT&amp;T's announcement on Wednesday of a Dollars 1bn joint
venture with industrial group Alfa to compete with Telmex in long-distance
services.
The IPC index closed 126.62 or 4.83 per cent off at 2,492.32. It was dragged
down by heavily weighted Telmex, which saw its 'L' shares plummet 8.62 per
cent and its 'A' stock drop 8.38 per cent.
Brazil
Equities in Sao Paulo gained a further 2.2 per cent in moderate trading as
sentiment was boosted by a successful share sale by Brazil's National
Development Bank (NDB).
The Bovespa index ended 1,076 higher at 49,926. Turnover was RDollars 258.5m
(Dollars 309.7m).
The NDB raised RDollars 91.1m with the sale of minority stakes in 13
companies, up 6.4 per cent from a minimum RDollars 85.6m combined asking
price for all stocks.
</TEXT>
