<HEADLINE>
FT  11 NOV 94 / World Commodities Prices: Wool
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Prices continue to fluctuate without a positive overall trend, at least in
the short term. A peak in mid-September was followed by a sharp setback, but
recovery from this failed to establish a new peak before the market fell
back slightly last week. This minor downturn also failed to develop further
and Australia's Eastern market indicator rose 9 cents to 790 during this
week's sales. The New Zealand market eased, with the indicator there down by
14 cents to 543 NZ cents a kg. The US dollar's fluctuations, which have
relevance for currencies in wool producing countries as well as for wool and
textile trade more widely, have tended to push up prices in many wool
textile manufacturing countries but have at the same time tended to make
buyers further down the trading line even more reluctant to operate.
</TEXT>
