<HEADLINE>
FT  11 NOV 94 / Royal to shed staff despite tripled profits
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS, Insurance Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Royal Insurance, the composite insurer, yesterday forecast a 10 per cent
reduction in its UK workforce over the next three years, in spite of a near
tripling of pre-tax profits in the first nine months to Pounds 311m.
Mr Richard Gamble, chief executive, said competitive pressures and the scope
offered by technology for cutting costs were forcing a reappraisal of
manpower levels across the group's operations. Jobs would be lost through
natural wastage.
Though the group's results underlined the strength of Royal's recovery from
heavy losses in the early 1990s, Mr Gamble acknowledged that the group had
benefited from exceptionally good trading conditions, particularly on
claims.
Reflecting its increase in pre-tax profits, up from Pounds 113m last time,
Royal also announced a switch in its investment strategy away from
fixed-interest securities. It invested an extra Pounds 250m in equities in
the nine-month period with the objective of boosting long-term capital
growth, rather than income.
Royal's results followed similarly buoyant figures earlier this week from
Commercial Union but neither have assuaged fears that the insurance industry
is entering a phase of intense pressure on margins over the next few years.
Highlighting the pressure on premium prices, Royal estimated private motor
rates had fallen by 5 per cent over the past year. Household policy rates
have also fallen in the past 12 months, while Royal estimates growth in
rates for commercial lines has slowed considerably.
Lex, Page 18
Details, Page 21
</TEXT>
