<HEADLINE>
FT  11 NOV 94 / Prudential set to reduce directors' service contracts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM LEWIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Prudential Corporation, the UK's largest investing institution, is
poised to follow the trend of other large companies and cut the length of
its directors' service contracts.
This follows mounting criticism from institutional shareholders of large
payouts to directors who have resigned while holding long service contracts
which entitle them to payouts of up to three times their basic salary.
The move would also be a significant reversal of the Prudential's policy on
directors' contracts. It has previously given three-year rolling contracts
strong support. Last June it said: 'If we want to recruit and retain the
right quality of executive on to our board, we need to offer them a
competitive remuneration package and currently a three-year contract is part
of that deal.'
This comment was in response to the launch of a campaign by PosTel, the
Pounds 25bn pension fund, calling for a reduction in the length of service
contracts. PosTel votes against the election or re-election of directors
with rolling employment contracts longer than two years.
The Prudential's change of policy is likely to remove the possibility of
PosTel embarrassing the Pru at its annual meeting in May.
Sir Martin Jacomb, the chairman of PosTel, is due to become non-executive
chairman of the Prudential at that meeting.
Five executive directors at the Prudential, including Mr Mick Newmarch, the
chief executive, have three-year rolling contracts. These are likely to be
re-placed with shorter contracts - probably two-year rolling contracts -
following an examination by the board's remuneration committee.
'There is a recognition here now that three-year rolling contracts are
passe,' a senior Prudential executive said yesterday.
The company confirmed the study and the conclusion that 'the market seems to
be moving away from three-year rolling contracts'.
The Prudential denied that Sir Martin's appointment as chairman had
influenced its decision to launch the study.
The company added that it would not try to impose similar cuts in the length
of directors' contracts in the companies in which it holds shares.
Other big public companies, such as Guinness and British Gas, have recently
shortened their directors' contracts.
Lex, Page 18
</TEXT>
