<PROFILE>_AN-EKKDMADUFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>941111
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  11 NOV 94 / 'Leftwing elitists' take flak from victorious Republicans
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUREK MARTIN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The spirit of political co-operation so evident on the morning after the US
mid-term elections was fast evaporating yesterday, mostly because victorious
Republicans could not resist taking potshots at President Bill Clinton.
Several Republicans also warned the president not to frustrate
implementation of their legislative agenda on issues ranging from increased
defence spending and deeper cuts in social programmes to cuts in foreign
aid.
The most provocative comments came from Congressman Newt Gingrich, virtually
certain to become the next Speaker of the House and - mostly  - still trying
to be magnanimous in victory. He promised, for example, no longer to call
the president an enemy of 'normal' Americans, a favourite pre-election
epithet.
However, what he gave in 24 hours filled with media interviews he also took
away. He described Mr Clinton and his wife Hillary as 'counter-culture
McGovernicks', a derogatory reference to the leftwing Democratic
presidential candidate of 1972. The current White House, he said, was
dominated by 'leftwing elitists'.
Warming to his familiar conservative theme, he said: 'There are profound
things that went wrong, starting with the Great Society (President Lyndon
Johnson's social legislation) and the counter-culture, and until we address
them head-on we're going to have these problems.'
Mr Clinton, he said, would be 'very, very dumb' to try to stand in the way
of the conservative agenda he intended to get through Congress, including
the reintroduction of voluntary prayer in schools by a constitutional
amendment next year.
Mr Bill Archer a congressman from Texas who is likely to be the next
chairman of the House ways and means committee, also expanded on the
Republican tactical approach: 'We can't really get much of anything done
which the president does not want to sign, other than by constitutional
amendment.'
Senator Jesse Helms, the arch-conservative in line to take over the foreign
relations committee, promised deep cuts in foreign aid, including US
contributions to the United Nations and Nato.
Mr Gingrich also warned, only half-jokingly, that the Republicans could now
frustrate the president in other ways. Senator Robert Dole, as majority
leader, could control every appointment Mr Clinton sent up for ratification,
he said.
The president drew his own line in the sand at his Wednesday election
postmortem by promising to work with the new Republican majority in
Congress, but not to permit a return to the economic policies of the 1980s.
Mr Clinton yesterday humorously acknowledged the force of some Republican
positions. Imposing limits on the number of terms members of Congress may
serve, he said with a smile, 'looks better to me every day'.
Budget policy swings in political wind, Page 6
Editorial Comment, Page 17
</TEXT>
