<HEADLINE>
FT  11 NOV 94 / MPs to probe failed hospital: Founder denies that Scottish
healthcare project was flawed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, Scottish Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Government funding for Health Care International, the private hospital which
went into receivership on Wednesday only four months after opening, is to be
investigated by the Commons' public accounts committee.
This follows a request to the committee last month from Mr George Robertson,
shadow Scottish secretary, for an urgent inquiry into why Pounds 30m of
public money had been committed to what he described as a 'shaky' project.
Mr Robert Sheldon, Labour chairman of the committee, said it would meet soon
to decide how to carry out the investigation.
The public funds offered to HCI included Pounds 22m in regional selective
assistance, part of which had not been disbursed. Scottish Enterprise, the
development body, had lent HCI Pounds 4m and invested Pounds 1.4m.
The joint receivers, Mr Murdoch McKillop and Mr John Talbot of Arthur
Andersen, were called in on Wednesday after the French bank Credit Lyonnais
refused to accept a refinancing package for the hospital, which hit cash
flow problems because of a shortage of overseas patients.
Yesterday Dr Raphael Levey, one of the US founders of HCI, denied that the
concept of HCI was flawed. Its cash flow needs had initially exceeded
'patient flows' but in recent days it had been achieving a rate of
admissions that would have assured its viability.
'If we had had a bit more time and a bit more cash this catastrophe would
not have happened,' he said. The bank which had refused to continue
supporting the project was the one that was 'least close to the project'.
Some hopes for the hospital's future are being pinned on the Abu Dhabi
Investment Authority which owns 5 per cent of HCI's ordinary shares, and had
been prepared to put more equity into it before the company went into
receivership. HCI believes Abu Dhabi could also assure a substantial flow of
patients to the hospital.
Yesterday Mr Tony Blair, Labour leader, rejected criticism that Labour's
stance over HCI was based on dogma.
He said: 'The dogma lay with Conservative ministers who were determined to
plough so much money into a highly questionable and risky project.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Health Care International.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P8062 General Medical and Surgical Hospitals.
    P9199 General Government, NEC.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>COMP  Company News.
