<HEADLINE>
FT  11 NOV 94 / Silver soup tureens fetch glittering price
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONY THORNCROFT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A pair of elaborate 18th century silver tureens sold for just over Pounds 1m
at Sotheby's yesterday, Antony Thorncroft writes.
It was an auction record for English tureens, and Sotheby's said the tureens
 -made in 1744 for Henry Bromley, 1st Baron Montfort - were the most
important items of English silver to be offered at auction for a decade.
The buyer was anonymous, but Arab collectors have recently acquired many
similar examples of ornate silver.
The tureens - which each weigh 16lbs - were designed by Palladian architect
William Kent and made by goldsmith George Wickes. Their most distinctive
feature is handles in the form of horses' heads. The tureens cost Henry
Bromley Pounds 500.
