<HEADLINE>
FT  11 NOV 94 / Lady Porter lawyer says gerrymander charge 'was absurd'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROB EVANS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A district auditor was wrong to use the word 'gerrymandering' when he
accused Westminster City Council's former Conservative leader Dame Shirley
Porter of mis-using public money, her lawyer claimed at a public inquiry
yesterday.
Mr Anthony Scrivener QC was defending Dame Shirley against accusations from
Mr John Magill, district auditor, that she and nine others sold off council
homes to people who they believed were likely to vote Conservative.
Mr Scrivener said it was 'absurd' to call it gerrymandering because there
was no way of guaranteeing that the buyers would vote - let alone that they
would vote Conservative. 'This was not gerrymandering,' he said. 'I can
hardly imagine a more emotive word to hit the headlines.'
At the start of the public inquiry, Dame Shirley tried to get Mr Magill
removed from the case because he had used such a term when presenting his
provisional report in January to a televised press conference. She claimed
it had prejudiced her defence.
Mr Scrivener said he appreciated it would be difficult for Mr Magill 'to
retreat from your high point' after the views had attracted so much
publicity. 'But I hope that you will have the strength to do just that,' he
said.
Mr Scrivener also argued that Mr Jeremy Sullivan, a leading QC, had approved
the scheme to sell the homes before it had been passed in July 1987. Mr
Scrivener said Dame Shirley attached great importance to obtaining legal
approval for her policies as council leader.
He added that if the district auditor stuck to his report, it would be the
first time that councillors would be surcharged after obtaining legal
approval from independent counsel.
Mr Scrivener criticised Mr Magill for going further than any other district
auditor when he sought and seized papers arising out of closed meetings of
Tory councillors. He alleged that Mr Magill had 'feasted' on these political
papers and had used them to back his accusations of gerrymandering. Mr
Scrivener did not deny these papers existed.
He told the inquiry: 'What was said in these meetings is one thing. It does
not mean that councillors forget their duties when they go into the council
chamber. If the district auditor is right, I can imagine that all the
shredders in councils around the country would be working overtime.'
The inquiry was adjourned until Tuesday.
</TEXT>
