<HEADLINE>
FT  11 NOV 94 / Heathrow tunnel probe focuses on design
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR, Construction Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Investigators into the tunnel collapse at Heathrow Airport are concentrating
their inquiries on the possibility that human error or design problems may
have caused the collapse.
BAA, the airport authority, confirmed yesterday that its inquiry had found
nothing so far to suggest that the New Austrian Tunnelling Method being used
to excavate two new underground stations beneath the airport was unsuitable
for use in London clay.
The investigation led by Mr David Williams, BAA's projects director, is
working closely with the Health and Safety Executive which is conducting a
separate inquiry into the collapse.
BAA said that both investigations were 'focusing inquiries on the design,
workmanship and the physical ground conditions in the area'. They will
examine work being done at the base of the main concourse tunnel close to
Terminal Four where an initial ground movement led to the collapse.
Investigators are also likely to look at monitoring equipment and procedures
used to provide early warning of ground movements. In normal circumstances
these would have been expected to allow sufficient time to strengthen the
tunnel and prevent a collapse.
Work has halted on the two Heathrow stations - which will form part of a
Pounds 300m rail link between the airport and Paddington Station in central
London - pending a clear outcome of the inquiries.
The preliminary findings of the BAA investigation may encourage managers of
the Pounds 1.9bn Jubilee Underground line extension. Work was halted at two
new stations on the extension - Waterloo and London Bridge - also being
built using the Austrian method.
</TEXT>
