<HEADLINE>
FT  11 NOV 94 / Food lobby welcomes healthy diet guidelines: Report urges
eating changes to cut heart disease
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RODERICK ORAM, Consumer Industries Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Food manufacturers broadly welcomed yesterday a report recommending changes
in diet to help reduce the UK's level of coronary heart disease, which is
among the highest in Europe.
Leaks about the report during the summer prompted heavy lobbying by the Food
and Drink Federation and some of its members such as Cadbury Schweppes, the
confectionery and soft drink maker, Tate &amp; Lyle, the sugar refiner, and
United Biscuits.
They believed that the report by the cardiovascular review group of the
Committee on Medical Aspects of Food Policy (Coma) would make detailed
dietary recommendations suggesting, for example, cuts in consumption of
sweets and biscuits.
Yesterday, however, Dr Kenneth Calman, the government's chief medical
officer, distanced the government from some of the report's recommendations
such as a reduction in salt consumption. He also stressed that the
committee's recommendations were only broad guidelines from which people
could pick and chose and that the government's own nutrition targets
remained unchanged.
Mr Michael Mackenzie, director-general of the federation, said: 'We are very
pleased that Dr Calman put the Coma report in its proper context. It is up
to individual tastes, and you can't have a prescribed diet. We are
consumer-led companies and you will see companies adapting to changing
demands.'
Coma's most controversial recommendation was a one-third reduction in salt
consumption. The Salt Manufacturers' Association was 'appalled' by the
proposal.
Mr William Cortazzi, association chairman, said, 'scientists are extremely
polarised' over whether a reduction in salt intake reduces blood pressure,
'you can't live without salt and products taste revolting if they don't have
salt'.
Dr Calman said salt reduction was not a target of government policy and 'we
respect the differences' in scientific opinion.
He and other health professionals welcomed, however, the report as a first
effort to turn nutritional information into dietary guidelines the public
could more easily understand.
Dr Mac Armstrong, secretary of the British Medical Association, said: 'What
the public really needs is clear, simple guidelines to cut through all the
claims and counter claims of the food advertising industry and tell them
what they really need to know. The Coma report does exactly that.'
A healthier diet would reduce the incidence of heart disease in Britain,
said Prof Michael Marmot, Coma chairman. It remained higher than all
European countries except Finland, the Republic of Ireland and the countries
of central and eastern Europe.
</TEXT>
