<HEADLINE>
FT  11 NOV 94 / Aerospace groups launch competitiveness campaign
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD GRAY, Defence Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Society of British Aerospace Companies yesterday launched a campaign to
improve competitiveness. The initiative flows from the Department of Trade
and Industry's white paper on competition, and is similar to that already
launched in the motor industry.
Mr Tim Eggar, industry minister, opened the scheme at a seminar in London.
The campaign is supported by large companies such as British Aerospace, GEC
and Rolls-Royce.
The society's Competitiveness Challenge encourages aerospace manufacturers
to share information about best industry practice and to co-operate to
deepen understanding between component suppliers and the big assembling
companies. It will use seminars, workshops and self-assessment
questionnaires to help companies understand where their advantages and
problems lie.
As well as the 200 members of the society, the information will be open to
800 other companies in allied fields which are being encouraged to join the
campaign. The scheme is intended to be self-financing, with companies being
charged for access to the information. The DTI has earmarked an annual grant
of Pounds 55,000 a year.
The aerospace industry has improved its balance of trade surplus in the past
decade, a distinction shared only by the chemical and pharmaceutical
industries.
</TEXT>
