<HEADLINE>
FT  11 NOV 94 / Farmers say proposals could be boost for horticulture
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DEBORAH HARGREAVES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Horticulture could receive a big boost from the change in eating patterns
encouraged by the Coma report if they are adopted widely by the public, the
National Farmers' Union said yesterday.
Fruit and vegetables account for annual sales of roughly Pounds 6bn with 82
per cent of vegetables and 15 per cent of fruit provided by home growers.
Large growers are already expanding to cope with increased demand and are
moving into further processing of fruit and vegetables to meet the needs of
supermarkets. For example, lettuce growers often package their own salads by
washing them and presenting leaves in a plastic bag as a way of meeting
consumer demands for convenience foods.
One NFU official said: 'If people do respond to this report, there is
clearly a big opportunity for certain sectors of agriculture and for others
more of a challenge.'
Demand for leaner meat is likely to prove more difficult for farmers. The
livestock industry has reduced the fat content of most meat considerably
over the past 20 years in response to the demands of healthier eating. The
pig and poultry sectors have had most success at reducing fat levels in meat
with the fat content in pork falling 35 per cent since 1975 to 3.5 per cent.
Farmers have reduced the fat content in beef by 15 per cent and lamb by 11
per cent to an average of 5.5 per cent. Some cuts of meat such as pork leg
now contain as little as 1.7 per cent fat.
The reduction in fat has been achieved by using low fat feeding programmes
and continental breeds of cattle rather than the indigenous Herefords and
Anguses, which are more fatty.
However Mr Martin Burtt, a livestock farmer from Yorkshire, said: 'You
cannot breed out fat entirely, meat has to have fat to give it flavour and
hold it together. We're close to optimum levels of fat now.'
Sir David Naish, NFU president, said: 'We have been encouraging farmers to
respond to signals from the marketplace and I believe this report, which
offers sensible guidelines on healthy eating, will help us to do that.'
</TEXT>
