<HEADLINE>
FT  11 NOV 94 / More builders cutting house prices
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR, Construction Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The number of builders trying to boost house sales with offers of price cuts
and free cars and holidays has risen sharply in recent weeks, a leading
house builder said yesterday.
The report by Mr Steve Morgan, chairman of Redrow, coincided with a survey
of 4,000 estate agents which showed a fall in all types of house sales last
month
The survey by Ombudsman for Corporate Estate Agents (OCEA) covering 26
estate agency chains and accounting for about half of UK house transactions,
showed a 7.5 per cent fall in net sales compared with October last year.
Sales were also 5.3 per cent lower than during September this year, said Mr
Peter Constable, chairman of OCEA.
The organisation did not blame the decrease on the half percentage point
rise in general interest rates announced in September.
It said: 'Housing activity declines towards the year end but sales volumes
have fallen rather earlier this year. This is due in part to potential
purchasers being distracted by high street retailers starting their
Christmas promotions earlier.
'Housing activity also tends to be dampened due to change to an Autumn
budget and house buying will decline further as we approach the peak festive
season.'
Mr Morgan, speaking to shareholders at Redrow's annual meeting, said: 'There
has been an unwelcome return in the new homes market to discounting in
recent times.'
Those builders with a December year end are thought to have stepped up
offers of discounts and incentives during the final few weeks of the year to
meet sales targets.
Mr Paul Pedley, Redrow's managing director said: 'You only have to look at
newspaper advertisements to see that more companies are offering incentives
to shift sales.'
Redrow, which was listed on the London Stock Exchange this year and is
expected to build more than 2,000 homes in 1994, said it did not expect the
trend to continue into 1995.
</TEXT>
