<HEADLINE>
FT  11 NOV 94 / S Korea to apply to OECD
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN BURTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SEOUL
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
South Korea expects to apply to join the Organisation for Economic
Co-operation and Development next month, the finance ministry said
yesterday. An application would follow Seoul's acceptance - expected by the
end of the month - as an observer on the OECD's financial market committee.
Negotiations are planned to start in the second half of 1995, with a goal of
membership approval by June 1996. However, they are expected to be
contentious, since the OECD is demanding that plans for financial
liberalisation be accelerated, while Korea argues that this would harm the
economy. Seoul is planning to phase out state-supported industrial loans and
deregulate interest rates, while opening financial markets gradually to
foreign investors and cutting curbs on capital flows. North Korea yesterday
gave a cool response to South Korea's recent move to resume economic
co-operation. A commentary by Pyongyang's central news agency demanded that
Seoul apologise for suspending economic ties over the nuclear dispute and
repeal its national security law before co-operation could begin.
