<HEADLINE>
FT  11 NOV 94 / Bosnian Serbs wary of move to state of war
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL ADAMS and REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PALE, BOSNIA, ZAGREB
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
With artillery fire occasionally audible in the distance, representatives of
the Bosnian Serbs have gathered in Pale, above Sarajevo, to consider how
much freedom of action to give their leader, Mr Radovan Karadzic.
Yesterday, after two days of debate behind firmly closed doors, it was clear
that the Bosnian Serb 'parliament' would stop well short of declaring a
state of war throughout its territory in Bosnia.
Mr Karadzic - facing mixed fortunes on the battlefield, a boycott by his
former protectors in Belgrade, and isolation from the wider world - would
like carte blanche to wage all-out war. But fearing a dilution of its
authority, the makeshift assembly has forced him to limit the scope of any
declaration of emergency rule to those areas most immediately at risk from
the latest fighting.
Officials say the formal state of war will apply only to some 50 per cent of
Serb-controlled territory.
'Of course, you can always expect resistance,' said an official close to the
Pale leadership. 'People got scared by all this talk of declaring war. But
we have to prove to the Moslems that they cannot win.'
Mr Karadzic said before yesterday's debate that he would assume certain
powers from the assembly but insisted there was no question of it being
dissolved.
The parliament has often been dismissed as a rubber stamp for the Bosnian
Serb leadership, but it does represent Mr Karadzic's link with a population,
part of which is not always necessarily behind him. He cannot afford to be
seen ignoring the interests of the representatives. Officials admit that
absenteeism and black marketeering, sometimes across enemy lines, have
resulted in military weakness.
The new measures will include more efficient mobilisation (which has already
begun), restrictions on civilian movement and introduction of martial law.
Local government will be concentrated in small groups of officials, directly
answerable to Mr Karadzic. 'It will not be a classic state of war, but a
semi-state of war,' said Mr Aleksa Buha, the 'foreign minister'. 'This is a
very serious decision. We don't want to do it too fast.'
Punishments for desertion and dereliction of duty are likely to be
toughened. On Wednesday, Mr Karadzic said several brigade commanders
responsible for losing territory near the north-western enclave of Bihac had
already been replaced for disobeying orders.
Since Serbia severed relations with the Bosnian Serbs in August, Mr Karadzic
has conducted periodic purges of the army and police, aimed at rooting out
those who might not think twice about taking their orders from Belgrade. An
official in Pale said the dismissals were 'a normal consequence' of the
breakdown in relations.
But it is clear that the Bosnian Serb leader's personal feud with President
Slobodan Milosevic has led him, rightly or wrongly, to suspect those around
him.
Reuter adds from Zagreb: Croatia hinted yesterday that it might attack rebel
Krajina Serbs if they keep firing from Croatia across the border at Moslems
in Bosnia. Krajina Serb artillery has been hammering government positions in
Moslem-populated Bihac since Tuesday and a Krajina Serb jet launched two
missiles into Bihac town yesterday. 'We believe Croatia will do something if
this continues,' said Mr Gojko Susak, defence minister.
</TEXT>
