<HEADLINE>
FT  11 NOV 94 / Bosnian Serbs ponder whether to declare war
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL ADAMS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PALE, BOSNIA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
After 2 1/2 years of war, the self-styled Bosnian Serb parliament yesterday
devoted a second day to the question of whether to make the conflict
official.
Despite waging a brutal conflict against Moslem and Croat enemies, and
incurring Nato air strikes, the Bosnian Serb leadership has never formally
declared war. But recent setbacks on the battlefields, coupled with the
effects of a three-month political and economic blockade by neighbouring
Serbia and Montenegro, have forced the Bosnian Serb leader, Mr Radovan
Karadzic, to impose new discipline.
Fearing a dilution of its authority, the makeshift parliament in Pale, above
Sarajevo, has forced Mr Karadzic to limit the scope of a declaration to
those areas most immediately at risk from the latest fighting. Political
sources in Pale say the formal state of war will apply only to half the
Serb-controlled territory.
'Of course, you can always expect resistance,' said a source close to the
Pale leadership. 'People got scared by all this talk of declaring war. But
we have to prove to the Moslems that they cannot win.'
The parliamentary session was conducted in private. Journalists were kept at
arms' length by order of Mr Sonja Karadzic, daughter of the Bosnian Serb
leader.
Mr Karadzic said before the debate continued yesterday that he would assume
certain decision-making powers from parliament, but insisted there was no
question of the assembly being dissolved.
As the Serbs come under military pressure he needs to take care. The
parliament has often been dismissed as a rubber stamp for the Bosnian Serb
political and military leadership, but it does represent Mr Karadzic's link
with the people, not all of whom are always behind him. He cannot afford to
be seen to be ignoring their representatives.
Officials admit that absenteeism and black marketeering, sometimes across
enemy lines, have resulted in military weakness. While Serbs enjoyed
overwhelming superiority in the field, and Moslems and Croats fought among
themselves, the problems were not acute. But recent events have injected a
note of urgency.
The new measures will include more efficient mobilisation - this has already
begun - restrictions on the movement of civilians and the introduction of
martial law. Local government will be concentrated in the hands of small
groups of officials, answerable to Mr Karadzic.
Punishments for desertion and dereliction of duty are likely to be
toughened. On Wednesday, Mr Karadzic said a number of brigade commanders
responsible for losing territory near the north western enclave of Bihac had
already been replaced for failing to obey orders.
With the sound of artillery occasionally audible in the placid streets of
this impoverished mountain resort, military uniforms seem more prevalent
than ever. Local radio programmes carry upbeat stories of the fighting
interspersed with detailed reports on the availability of food throughout
the self-proclaimed Bosnian Serb republic.
Since Serbia severed relations with the Bosnian Serbs in August, Mr Karadzic
has conducted periodic purges of the army and police. It is clear that his
personal feud with the Serbian president, Mr Slobodan Milosevic, has led
him, rightly or wrongly, to suspect those around him.
</TEXT>
