<HEADLINE>
FT  11 NOV 94 / Water company turns off party funds
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN RIDDING
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Lyonnaise des Eaux-Dumez, one of France's largest construction and utilities
groups, said yesterday it was halting political contributions following a
series of corruption investigations which have shaken French business and
political circles.
The announcement is the most significant move so far by French companies
which are seeking to defuse allegations of corruption. It could push other
large business groups to adopt a similar policy ahead of next spring's
presidential elections. Generale des Eaux, the principal rival of Lyonnaise
des Eaux, said yesterday it was reviewing its position on campaign
financing.
Utilities and public works companies are the largest corporate contributors
to political campaigns. Through their subsidiaries, some of them have been
linked to investigations of illicit financing of political parties.
Subsidiaries of Lyonnaise des Eaux, have been investigated in a case which
forced the resignation in July of Mr Alain Carignon, the former
communications minister.
Mr Carignon faces charges of receiving funding for his political campaigns
from a subsidiary of Lyonnaise des Eaux in return for public works contracts
in Grenoble, where he is mayor. Lyonnaise des Eaux denies any wrongdoing.
Mr Jerome Monod, chairman of Lyonnaise des Eaux, said yesterday that laws
relating to company contributions to political parties were complex and
unclear. He had decided 'to suspend all contributions to political parties
until new laws are promulgated to clarify appropriate conduct in this area'.
The move reflects concern among leading French business groups. 'It shows a
defensive attitude,' says Mr Francois Morin, director of Lerep, the economic
and political research institute. 'The large utilities groups have been
destabilised by the climate of corruption.'
The utilities groups are taking other steps to redress their image. Generale
des Eaux is drawing up a code of ethics relating to the conduct of company
officials in seeking public works contracts. It said yesterday it favoured
legislation either to prevent the direct financing of individual candidates
or restrict party financing to the national level.
The National Federation of Public Works is preparing a code by which its
6,000 member companies would promise not to offer bribes to win the FFr150bn
(Pounds 18bn) of public contracts they carry out each year. Bouygues, a
large construction group, has resisted the proposal and the implication of
previous wrongdoing, comparing the proposal to 'a motorist promising, from
tomorrow, to obey the highway code'.
However, the spate of corruption investigations which have prompted two
ministerial resignations and seen leading businessmen placed under
investigation, has prompted calls for stronger action. An all-party
parliamentary committee is discussing banning direct corporate funding of
political parties.
At present, a 1990 law limits to FFr500,000 the amount that a company can
donate to a political party. But the payment of donations through
subsidiaries has enabled groups to make much larger overall contributions.
In the 1993 parliamentary elections, for example, Lyonnaise des Eaux donated
about FFr7.7m to political parties.
</TEXT>
<XX>
