<HEADLINE>
FT  10 NOV 94 / International Company News: Salomon faces charge after
office shake-up
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Salomon, the parent company of Wall Street securities house Salomon
Brothers, announced yesterday that it may have to take a charge against its
earnings in the fourth quarter because of 'unreconciled balances' in its
books that were discovered during a reorganisation of the company's
back-office systems.
In its filing of third quarter results with the Securities and Exchange
Commission, Salomon said the charge might affect its operating results, but
would 'not be material to the company's financial condition' - an indication
that the company believed the problem would not seriously affect its
finances.
Although Salomon would not elaborate on a brief statement which said that
any net after-tax impact of any charges related to the unreconciled balances
would be 'insignificant,' sources close to the company said there was no
indication that the discrepancies resulted from fraud.
The imbalances were said to have been discovered while the company was
shifting its back-office technology from overloaded central processing
mainframe computers to a more flexible network of powerful personal
computers.
The bookkeeping mix-up comes at a difficult time for Salomon, which has been
hit by large losses on its investment banking and trading business this
year.
In the first nine months of 1994, the parent company lost Dollars 242m.
</TEXT>
