FT  10 NOV 94 / NZ party leader resigns
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TERRY HALL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WELLINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The New Zealand political outlook changed dramatically early today when Mr
Jim Anderton announced his surprise resignation as leader of the left wing
Alliance party. Mr Anderton had been widely expected to lead the party, a
grouping of left wing and green parties, to victory in the 1996 election. A
former president of the Labour party, he resigned because of Labour's right
wing economic policies in 1988, to form the Alliance. Until recently it had
enjoyed top poll ratings among political parties. Mr Anderton's daughter
committed suicide during last year's election campaign, and at a press
conference today he said he wished he had resigned then. Mr Anderton said he
would stay as MP until the next election and work for an Alliance victory.
</TEXT>
