<HEADLINE>
FT  10 NOV 94 / World Stock Markets (America): Dow gyrates wildly as
investors reassess poll
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA BRANSTEN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US share prices fluctuated wildly yesterday as markets struggled to gauge
the impact of broad Republican victories in Tuesday's congressional
elections, writes Lisa Bransten in New York.
At the close the Dow Jones Industrial Average was up a net 1.01 at 3,831.75.
The more broadly based Standard &amp; Poor's 500 lost just 0.25 at 465.40, while
the American Stock Exchange composite ended 0.2 firmer at 451.25 and the
Nasdaq composite 0.29 easier at 767.25. Trading volume on the New York SE
totalled 338m shares.
In early trading the Dow surged 38 points on optimism about Republican
control of Congress, but later in the morning the gain was wiped out as
concern about conflict between a Democratic president and Republican
legislature took hold. Program trading and investor profit-taking took the
Dow down a net 20 points at one stage, but prices recovered later in the
day.
In addition to uncertainty about the government, investors were waiting to
see the extent of interest rate increases expected to come out of next
Tuesday's meeting of the Federal Reserve's open market committee meeting.
Healthcare stocks got a boost from the election news as traders reacted
optimistically to the probable death of broad health reforms proposed by the
Democratic President, Mr Bill Clinton.
Shares of drugmakers were up broadly at the close in spite of some midday
volatility: Merck, a component of the Dow, gained Dollars 1 1/8 at Dollars
36 7/8 , Pfizer was up Dollars 1 3/4 at Dollars 76 1/8 , Bristol-Myers
Squibb added Dollars  1/2 at Dollars 58 7/8 and Eli Lilly put on Dollars 1
1/4 at Dollars 64 3/8 .
Defence contractors also got an initial boost from the markets as traders
ventured that Republican gains might stem decreases in defence spending.
After strong early rises, General Electric fell to end Dollars  3/8 off on
the day at Dollars 48 3/4 and Raytheon was up a net Dollars  3/8 at Dollars
63 7/8 . Northrop Grumman gained Dollars 1 1/4 at Dollars 44 1/2 and
Lockheed rose Dollars 1 1/4 to Dollars 73 1/2 .
Hospital companies Columbia/HCA Healthcare and National Medical Enterprises
also advanced and retreated with the markets. Columbia was up Dollars  5/8
at Dollars 41 1/4 and NME gained Dollars  1/8 at Dollars 14 1/2 .
Shares of Long Island Lighting, a New York City-area provider of gas and
electrical services, fell Dollars 1 1/4 to Dollars 16 1/2 on the defeat of
the incumbent state governor Mr Mario Cuomo, who had proposed state
acquisition of the utility.
In trading unrelated to the elections, the railroad Santa Fe Pacific rose
sharply by Dollars 1 1/2 to Dollars 16 1/8 after Union Pacific sweetened its
offer to Santa Fe shareholders. Union Pacific shares dropped Dollars 2 to
Dollars 47 1/2 . If the takeover is overturned by regulators, it could be
stuck with Santa Fe shares worth far less than the proposed purchase price.
SciMed Life Systems moved up Dollars 2 3/4 to Dollars 51 1/4 on news that
the medical device company would be bought by Boston Scientific for Dollars
865m in stock.
</TEXT>
