<HEADLINE>
FT  10 NOV 94 / International Capital Markets: Share surrogate that is easy
to trade and settle
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN BRICE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Depositary receipts have enjoyed such success because they can make buying
and selling equity in a company easier for international investors than
buying and selling the shares on a local stock exchange, writes Martin
Brice.
The depositary receipt represents ownership of shares which remain in
safe-keeping with a bank in the issuer's home market, often either Bank of
New York or Citibank. The receipt itself may be traded elsewhere. Dividend
payments are usually in US dollars, and voting rights are usually the same
as for the underlying stock.
There is little technical difference between a global depositary receipt
(GDR) and an American depositary receipt (ADR), although depositary receipts
listed in the US tend to be called ADRs while GDRs are often listed
elsewhere - for instance in Luxembourg and increasingly in London.
The first ADR was issued in 1927, but the first GDR came only four years
ago. The forthcoming listing by TeleWest, the UK cable television and
tele-communications company, on the US exchange Nasdaq will be called an
ADR, but may be bought by any international investor; the recent issue by
Bajaj Auto, the Indian scooter maker, was listed in London and called a GDR.
When investors buy and sell GDRs, settlement may be through Cedel, Euroclear
or DTC, the US settlement system.
The documents for issuing a GDR would cost a company around Dollars 100,000,
plus fees to the arranging bank of around 3 1/2 per cent of the total
raised. An ADR offered and listed in the US would cost a company up to
Dollars 1m, of which about half would go on lawyers' fees and much of the
rest on printing and accountants' fees, in addition to the bank's fee.
Where there are barriers to international investors gaining access to the
local stock market, the GDR may fetch a lower or higher price than the
shares in the home market. Citibank, the US bank, pioneered GDRs in 1990
with a Dollars 40m issue for the Korean company Samsung. Much of the
business is now sourced from investment banks in London, with Goldman Sachs
and Jardine Fleming the leaders.
About 90 GDRs are traded via Seaq International and listed on the Luxembourg
stock exchange. Around 275 ADRs are listed in the US.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
    USZ  United States of America.
    LUZ  Luxembourg, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6231 Security and Commodity Exchanges.
</IN>
<XX>
