<HEADLINE>
FT  10 NOV 94 / International Capital Markets: Four-year surge in ADR and
GDR issues - Emerging markets have put depositary receipts in the spotlight
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN BRICE and RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The global depositary receipt has been thrust into the spotlight by the
increasing globalisation of equity markets and a steep increase in demand
for capital from companies in the emerging markets of Latin America, Asia
and eastern Europe.
Since its birth with the first humble Dollars 40m issue in 1990, the market
for global depositary receipts (GDRs) has experienced rapid growth. Issues
to date this year exceed Dollars 5.5bn, an increase by a factor of more than
a hundred times since 1990.
The more traditional American depositary receipt (ADR) has also seen a surge
in issuance from companies in emerging markets, following the modification
of US securities laws in 1990.
The passage by the Securities and Exchange Commission of Rule 144a amended
securities legislation governing private placement issues to 'qualified
institutional buyers' - effectively large institutions.
This eliminated the holding period - the period of time for which buyers
must hold shares before trading them - and introduced greater liquidity to
the US market.
Foreign companies can also raise capital through the 144a market without
incurring the expensive regulatory and accounting burdens entailed with the
direct issue of shares.
'The rule 144a market has had a very positive effect on the globalisation of
the US capital market,' said Mr Mark Bach, global sales director of
Citibank, which launched so-called rule 144a depositary receipts in 1990 and
now acts as depositary for 41 per cent of the issuers launching depositary
receipts.
The rate of growth of this instrument has outpaced that of the international
bond markets, where issuance doubled to Dollars 481bn between 1990 and 1993.
During the first nine months of 1994, 184 companies from 40 countries
launched new ADR or GDR programmes, compared with only 96 during the same
period of last year. In the third quarter alone 80 companies launched
programmes, up 135 per cent on last year's figures.
Emerging market issuers now account for 61 per cent of the new depositary
receipts, compared with 11 per cent of new programmes issued in 1990.
'The emerging markets are by far the fastest growing segment of the
depositary receipt business today,' notes Mr Bach.
Aside from the rapid growth in global equity issues in general and the
growing popularity of foreign issues for US investors, two other other
factors help explain the popularity of the depositary receipt mechanism for
companies in emerging markets seeking to raise capital from institutions in
the United States, Europe and Asia.
Depositary receipt programmes allow investors to circumvent problems caused
by poor or unwieldy settlement systems.
That has been a particularly attractive factor in India, where the Bombay
Stock Exchange has a 45-day settlement period.
It could also play an important part in expanding the DR market as companies
in Russia, where settlement systems are primitive, seek to raise capital on
world markets.
International investors have little confidence in the ability of domestic
institutions to safeguard securities, which makes trade in the depositary
receipt proxy an attractive alternative.
Kleinwort Benson, the UK merchant bank, is planning a multi-billion GDR
issue for Gazprom, the country's giant gas company, which aims to sell a 9
per cent stake to international investors next year.
Last week, international trading in shares held by a Cyprus-based holding
company of RNGS, the giant Russian oil and gas construction company, began.
The shares are held by the holding company, which in turn holds the RNGS
shares, along the lines of a depositary receipt issue.
The use of a depositary receipt allows international investors access to
equity markets which would otherwise be out of reach.
Jardine Fleming, the UK-based investment bank, has constructed a Dollars
250m issue for Benpres, the largest broadcasting group in the Philippines,
to allow foreigners to own receipts but not the underlying shares. Local
legislation places restrictions on the foreign ownership of the shares of
media companies.
Among big issuers of depositary receipts this year are Korean companies,
which have raised Dollars 473.9m so far in 1994, bringing total issuance by
companies from the country to Dollars 1.19bn since 1990.
Last month Korea Electric Power, Korea's biggest company by capitalisation,
became the country's second company to list on the New York Stock Exchange,
when it raised Dollars 300m in a global equity offering of 14.9m ADRs.
October also saw one of Asia's biggest ever international equity offerings
through DRs, when Indosat, Indonesia's international telecommunications
company, raised more than Dollars 720m through an issue of 22.5m ADRs.
Citibank also singles out Hong Kong (17 issues), Brazil (16 issues) and
Mexico (16 issues) and South Africa (10 issues) as highly active issuers of
depositary receipts in the first nine months of this year.
However, growth has been particularly rapid in India, where more than 29
companies have issued depositary receipt programmes in the first nine months
of the year. Indian companies have raised more than Dollars 2.2bn in DR
issues alone so far this year compared with less than Dollars 900m last
year. And since the first Indian DR was issued in 1992, 50 Indian companies
have received almost Dollars 4bn of the Dollars 11bn raised from DR issues.
Mr Ian Hannam, a director of Jardine Fleming, believes India has many
attractions over other emerging markets. 'The real attractions are the
existence of a middle class the size of the entire USA, and a recognised
legal and accounting framework for the ownership of assets.'
The absence of a legal framework for the ownership of assets is a problem
for the emerging economies of eastern Europe, but not for India, he said.
Despite the uncertainty surrounding the prospective sale of Videsh Sanchar
Nigam (VSNL), the state-controlled international telecommunications
monopoly, prospects are still regarded as good, with overall DR issuance
alone in India expected to climb to Dollars 2.5bn by the end of the year.
Indeed, the Indian DR market could be about to enter a new phase following
the change in rules governing the issuance of DRs. The government has ended
the use of warrants, which give investors the right to buy shares at a fixed
price in the future.
Warrants were often used to make an offer more attractive, since they could
be priced more cheaply than existing shares.
The end of warrants is likely to mean a two-tier market emerging for Indian
GDRs, believe some investment bankers.
Whereas blue-chip companies such as Bajaj Auto, whose issue was priced at a
premium to the underlying share, are likely to find an enthusiastic welcome,
second-line companies are likely to struggle, bankers believe.
However, with more than 20 permissions given by the Indian government for
fundraising issues of Dollars 100m currently outstanding, the GDR has an
active future.
At least one London merchant bank is believed to be looking at using GDRs to
finance telecom projects in India, which is likely to remain the biggest
market for GDRs.
