<HEADLINE>
FT  10 NOV 94 / International Company News: US operations help News Corp
rise 15%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRUCE JACQUES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SYDNEY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
News Corporation, Mr Rupert Murdoch's international media group, has begun
the financial year with a solid rise in net earnings following strong
results from the company's film and television operations in the US.
News Corp yesterday announced a 15 per cent rise in net profit to ADollars
301m (USDollars 232m) in the three months to end-September, from ADollars
262m a year ago, on a 7.6 per cent increase in operating revenue to ADollars
2.99bn from ADollars 2.78bn.
A 43 per cent rise in earnings from associated companies and a lower net
interest bill also helped earnings. However, Australian and UK newspaper
interests were flat.
Most of its earnings came from the US, where operating income rose to
ADollars 283m from ADollars 248m. Directors said profits from Twentieth
Century Fox films had doubled in the quarter following successful releases
such as Speed and True Lies. Results from the Fox television station group
were also up strongly.
Magazine and inserts results, where operating income rose to ADollars 74m
from ADollars 70m ,benefited from higher pricing and advertising revenues.
But earnings from the HarperCollins book publishing operation eased to
ADollars 65m from ADollars 76m, reflecting weaker results from the San
Francisco group.
Operating income from UK operations fell to ADollars 65m from ADollars 75m,
with directors citing the impact of The Times newspaper's price cut in June.
'Circulation at The Times now stands at 607,143, an increase of more than 37
per cent versus a year ago,' they said.
'At The Sun, circulation remains in excess of 4m copies following a 2p
cover-price rise on August 22. On the advertising front, revenues are up
across all titles, due to an improving advertising market and higher
circulation levels.'
Directors said BSkyB, the company's 50 per cent owned satellite broadcasting
subsidiary (in which Pearson, owner of the Financial Times, has a stake),
achieved a significant increase in operating profit, with total subscribers
exceeding 3.6m.
The company's Australia and Pacific Basin region saw the biggest segmental
earnings fall, with operating income down to ADollars 40m from ADollars 89m.
Directors said revenue gains had been offset by higher depreciation charges
due to plant modernisation.
Star TV, the 64 per cent owned satellite broadcasting subsidiary, incurred a
loss.
Ansett, the 50 per cent owned Australian airline, continued to increase
earnings, and with BSkyB, lifted the contribution from associated companies
to ADollars 106m from ADollars 74m.
News Corp's direct operating income fell by 5.8 per cent to ADollars 388m
from ADollars 412m, mainly reflecting last year's sale of the South China
Morning Post and unfavourable exchange rates. However, currency changes also
contributed to a fall in interest expense to ADollars 154m from ADollars
173m.
Tax provisions took ADollars 47m compared with ADollars 39m. This excludes a
ADollars 3m abnormal profit, compared with a ADollars 16m loss previously.
US operations contributed the biggest share of group revenues, up to
ADollars 2.2bn from ADollars 1.93bn. UK revenues eased to ADollars 469m from
ADollars 471m and Australian revenues were down to ADollars 375m from
ADollars 382m.
</TEXT>
