<HEADLINE>
FT  10 NOV 94 / International Company News: Improved sales lift Federated to
Dollars 44.3m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Increased sales and improved efficiency helped Federated Department Stores,
the US owner of Bloomingdale's and other department store chains, to produce
a surge in net income from Dollars 20.3m to Dollars 44.3m in its third
quarter to Octo-ber.
The increase in earnings was exaggerated by a tax adjustment in the
comparable period, but Federated said net income would still have been 26
per cent ahead if the adjustment had not taken place.
Earnings a share rose to 35 cents in the quarter from 16 cents.
Some of the profits increase came from an 8 per cent rise in revenues to
Dollars 1.93bn.
Federated opened four new stores during the period, taking the total to 235,
while sales at existing stores rose by 3.4 per cent.
Gross margins fell to 38.5 per cent from 39.5 per cent because Federated
marked down prices to shift goods. However, the effects were outweighed by
its continuing efforts to increase efficiency: operating costs were down
from 33.8 per cent of sales to 31.7 per cent.
In July Federated won agreement from R. H. Macy, the rival department store
group, to a merger but the deal is not expected to be completed until the
end of the year and is not reflected in the figures.
Nordstrom, a US clothing retailer with 55 large stores, reported a 50 per
cent increase in net income from Dollars 25.5m to Dollars 38.1m in the
quarter to October, continuing the strong profits growth seen earlier in the
year.
Earnings a share increased from 31 cents to 46 cents.
The company said higher sales revenues, fewer markdowns and greater control
over costs were behind the increase.
Revenues rose by 12 per cent to Dollars 862m, with existing stores
increasing sales by 6.7 per cent and the rest coming from new stores.
</TEXT>
