<HEADLINE>
FT  10 NOV 94 / International Company News: Electrolux posts seven-fold
improvement
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER BROWN-HUMES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A seven-fold rise in profits at Electrolux in the first nine months was
powered by cost-cutting, big capital gains, and economic recovery in western
Europe.
The world's biggest manufacturer of household appliances saw income after
financial items jump to SKr5.08bn (Dollars 698m) from SKr712m.
The sale of three non-core industrial units produced capital gains of
SKr2.77bn and lifted operating income to SKr6.26bn from SKr2.01bn.
Without the gain, operating income was 73 per cent higher at SKr3.48bn while
income after financial items was up 224 per cent at SKr2.31bn. Earnings per
share climbed to SKr19.8 from SKr2. Electrolux B shares closed SKr9.5 higher
at SKr365.5.
Mr Leif Johansson, chief executive, said the underlying improvement was
mainly due to the group's restructuring and cost-cutting programme which has
lifted productivity by 10 per cent over the past year.
However, he said market conditions in Europe and the US were better,
reflected in an 8 per cent underlying increase in sales to SKr79.8bn.
The recovery has been driven by household appliances, the biggest of the
group's four divisions.
The group said there were signs that the pace of increase in demand in North
America was slowing, while momentum was increasing in most European markets.
'We are also starting to see some price increases in the European household
appliance market,' he said, although he noted that the group's own raw
material costs were also rising.
Sales of household appliances rose 9.2 per cent to SKr47.6bn. Operating
income showed 'a marked improvement' driven by a strong performance from the
group's US and European white goods units.
The group's three other divisions, commercial appliances, outdoor products
and industrial products, improved operating income.
In the third quarter, group income after financial items climbed to SKr650m
from SKr107m after an 8 per cent rise in underlying sales to SKr24.2bn.
There was a stronger performance from the group's commercial appliances
division, which suffered from weak demand in the first six months.
</TEXT>
