<HEADLINE>
FT  10 NOV 94 / Co-op Bank owner considers proposals for sell-off plan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HAMILTON FAZEY, Northern Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The sale of part or all of the Co-operative Bank is being considered by its
owner, the Co-operative Wholesale Society.
SG Warburg, the investment bank, has the commission to examine selling
shares in the bank to another co-operative financial institution. Since last
year, contact is believed to have been made with co-operative banks in
Canada, Germany, France, Belgium and Switzerland.
The CWS board discussed a paper on the bank's future last week, but decided
to take no short-term action.
The Manchester-based bank is a small player, with only 3,500 employees and 2
per cent of the UK retail market. However, it is strong in two niches: gold
cards and local government accounts.
It has also attracted customers by refusing to do business with companies
that it considers insensitive to environmental issues.
The Co-op Bank's asset base was Pounds 3.4bn in its accounts for the year to
January 8, with pre-tax profits of Pounds 17.8m.
The CWS was founded in 1863 and set up the bank nine years later. As owner
of 100 per cent of the equity, the CWS has to guarantee the bank's capital
base.
Returns have been poor because the bank has had to retain profits to keep
its base strong.
An alternative recommended in last week's board discussion paper was to
transfer ownership to the Co-operative Insurance Society, although this
would be unlikely to be approved by the Bank of England.
The bank's chairman, Mr Tom Agar, former chief executive of the Lincoln
Co-operative Retail Society, was unable to attend the meeting and Mr Terry
Thomas, chief executive, does not have a seat on the CWS board, which is
elected by the co-operative movement.
Mr Thomas, who joined from Barclays Bank, has played a key role in the Co-op
Bank's recent emergence.
The CWS came close to selling 49 per cent of its equity five years ago to DG
Bank of Germany.
The deal depended on the Co-op Bank winning the competition for Girobank,
which the government unexpectedly sold to the Alliance and Leicester
Building Society.
</TEXT>
