<HEADLINE>
FT  10 NOV 94 / Private hospital fails despite Pounds 30m aid from
government
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON and ALAN PIKE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Health Care International, the Scottish private hospital opened four months
ago to cater for overseas patients, went into receivership yesterday when
its bankers failed to agree a rescue package.
The hospital, located in an enterprise zone at Clydebank near Glasgow, had
been unable to attract enough patients - only 20 of its 260 beds were
occupied yesterday. Its failure is highly embarrassing for the government,
which committed a total of Pounds 30m to the Pounds 180m project.
Mr George Robertson, shadow Scottish secretary, accused Scottish Office
ministers of 'recklessly gambling public money on a shaky, ill-conceived
project', while the Scottish TUC described the hospital as 'a harebrained
scheme which common sense indicated was doomed to fail'.
HCI, which employes 400 people, hit a financial crisis in late September
because of a severe shortage of patients from its targeted markets of Italy,
Greece and the Middle East.
Mr Ian Lang, Scottish secretary, said the possibility of the hospital's now
being taken over by the NHS was 'not part of our plan'. He hoped it would be
possible for the project to be taken forward following receivership 'in
pursuit of the original objectives of the company'.
Though modern, the hospital is unlikely to interest other UK independent
hospital operators, having already shown that a Scottish hospital aimed at
the overseas market is not viable. Its use as a conventional private
hospital is restricted by its location in an area with powerful pro-NHS
traditions.
London private hospitals used to rely heavily on overseas patients,
particularly from the Middle East, but this market has reduced in recent
years. Most hospital operators now balance overseas work with UK patients.
Samuel Montagu, leader of the syndicate of five banks lending to HCI,
appointed Mr Murdoch McKillop and Mr John Talbot of Arthur Andersen as joint
receivers.
Although new equity funding was available from the Abu Dhabi Investment
Company, the French bank Credit Lyonnais, one of five in the lending
syndicate, refused to agree to the package, precipitating receivership. It
said yesterday a viable refinancing plan had not been forthcoming.
HCI was conceived by two Harvard professors, Dr Angelo Eraklis and Dr
Raphael Levey. The equity investors are led by Harvard Management, which
invests money for Harvard University.
The Pounds 30m of public funds offered to HCI included Pounds 22m in
regional selective assistance, only some of which had been paid. Scottish
Enterprise, the development body, had lent HCI Pounds 4m and invested Pounds
1.4m.
</TEXT>
